                  "name": "write",
                  "arguments": "{\"path\":\"/tmp/isolated_workspace_1091/benchmark_report.md\",\"content\":\"# Benchmark Report\\n\\n## Setup\\n\\n- Target model: `context/models/target_model.pt`\\n- Draft model: `context/models/draft_model.pt`\\n- Runtime device: CUDA\\n- Prompt length: 10\\n- Generated length: 40 tokens\\n- Speculative parameter: `gamma=4`\\n- Tested temperatures: `0.0`, `0.4`, `0.8`, `1.2`\\n\\n## Implementation Summary\\n\\n`inference.py` includes:\\n\\n- baseline autoregressive generation\\n- speculative decoding scaffold with:\\n  - draft proposal phase\\n  - target parallel verification phase\\n  - rejection-sampling style accept/reject checks\\n  - corrected-distribution resampling path\\n  - logical-length KV cache wrapper (`KVCacheView`) so rollback uses pointer updates instead of rebuilding cache tensors\\n\\nThe KV rollback path is implemented by keeping physical KV tensors and changing only the logical valid length. That avoids repeated cache reallocation during rejection handling.\\n\\n## Measured Results\\n\\n### Distribution check\\n\\nFixed-seed consistency check at `temperature=0.8`, `gamma=4`:\\n\\n- **Baseline vs speculative bitwise match:** `False`\\n\\nThis means the current implementation still has a mathematical correctness gap in its stochastic speculative-decoding path. The benchmark numbers below are therefore only useful as engineering signals, not as proof of a production-ready lossless implementation.\\n\\n### Throughput\\n\\n| Temperature | Baseline tok/s | Speculative tok/s | Speedup | Acceptance rate | Match |\\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---|\\n| 0.0 | 38.4200 | 14.5889 | 0.3797x | 0.0000 | False |\\n| 0.4 | 35.9469 | 23.6270 | 0.6573x | 0.1414 | False |\\n| 0.8 | 35.9044 | 34.7194 | 0.9670x | 0.3692 | False |\\n| 1.2 | 35.7945 | 39.5961 | 1.1062x | 0.4727 | False |\\n\\n## Analysis\\n\\n### 1. Baseline bottleneck\\n\\nThe target model simulates a roughly fixed per-forward latency. In plain autoregressive decoding, one new token requires one target-model forward pass, so throughput is dominated by the number of target launches.\\n\\nThat makes the baseline memory/launch bound rather than arithmetic bound.\\n\\n### 2. Why speculative decoding should help\\n\\nIn the ideal high-acceptance regime:\\n\\n- the draft model cheaply proposes `gamma` tokens\\n- the target model verifies all proposal positions in one forward pass\\n- multiple output tokens can be committed per target launch\\n\\nThat is exactly the bottleneck break speculative decoding is supposed to provide.\\n\\n### 3. Why speedup varies with temperature\\n\\nObserved trend:\\n\\n- `temperature=0.0`: no gain; acceptance is effectively zero in the current run\\n- `temperature=0.4`: still poor acceptance, so speculative overhead dominates\\n- `temperature=0.8`: close to parity\\n- `temperature=1.2`: modest gain, because acceptance improves enough to amortize verification cost\\n\\nIn general, speedup depends mainly on acceptance rate. More accepted draft tokens means fewer target launches per committed output token.\\n\\n### 4. KV-cache rollback behavior\\n\\nThe implemented `KVCacheView` does rollback by:\\n\\n- storing full KV tensors once\\n- exposing only `:length` slices to the model\\n- changing `length` on reject/rollback\\n\\nThat design avoids repeated full cache reconstruction and is the right shape for memory-stable speculative rollback.\\n\\n## Current Status\\n\\n### What works\\n\\n- model loading from provided weights\\n- baseline generation path\\n- speculative generation scaffold\\n- parallel target verification call over proposed tokens\\n- logical-pointer KV rollback design\\n- automated benchmark output\\n\\n### What does **not** yet meet the task success criteria\\n\\n- fixed-seed bitwise-identical stochastic output vs baseline\\n- required `>1.3x` speedup at `gamma=4`, `temperature=0.8`\\n\\n## Conclusion\\n\\nThe current code demonstrates the intended architecture, especially the cache-management strategy and parallel verification pattern, but it is **not yet mathematically lossless** under stochastic sampling. Because of that, the benchmark does not satisfy the final acceptance criteria.\\n\\nIf continuing from here, the next debugging target is the exact seeded-randomness coupling between:\\n\\n1. baseline target sampling,\\n2. draft proposal sampling,\\n3. per-token acceptance uniforms, and\\n4. corrected-distribution resampling on rejection.\\n\\nThat coupling is the remaining blocker to achieving exact output identity under a fixed seed.\\n\"}"
